00:06:11.070 --> 00:06:16.070
we have a category A recommendation to, I don't know,

125
00:06:18.090 --> 00:06:20.604
put peanut butter on white bread.

126
00:06:20.604 --> 00:06:23.168
And this came from doing a study

127
00:06:23.168 --> 00:06:26.040
of 100 kids in elementary school

128
00:06:26.040 --> 00:06:28.020
where 50 were given peanut butter on bread

129
00:06:28.020 --> 00:06:30.648
and 50 were given nothing on bread.

130
00:06:30.648 --> 00:06:32.970
So we got a randomized controlled trial here.

131
00:06:32.970 --> 00:06:34.890
You know, somehow they didn't know what they got.

132
00:06:34.890 --> 00:06:39.000
Would this be sufficient for an A recommendation?

133
00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:40.080
And you'd need to know, oh yeah,

134
00:06:40.080 --> 00:06:42.120
that's a randomized controlled trial.

135
00:06:42.120 --> 00:06:43.260
And if it was positive,

136
00:06:43.260 --> 00:06:45.210
that's gonna be a sure A recommendation

137
00:06:45.210 --> 00:06:47.250
because it's based on consistent,

138
00:06:47.250 --> 00:06:48.870
good quality, patient-oriented evidence.

139
00:06:48.870 --> 00:06:52.590
And we looked at this, if it's an A recommendation,

140
00:06:52.590 --> 00:06:56.490
it's typically a systematic review, a meta analysis,

141
00:06:56.490 --> 00:06:59.895
a high-quality randomized control trial.

142
00:06:59.895 --> 00:07:01.830
A B recommendation is gonna be

143
00:07:01.830 --> 00:07:04.402
some kind of observational study,

144
00:07:04.402 --> 00:07:06.750
cohort study, case control study,

145
00:07:06.750 --> 00:07:08.403
cross-sectional study,

146
00:07:08.403 --> 00:07:12.000
might be a case reporter case series.

147
00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:13.410
And then a C recommendation

148
00:07:13.410 --> 00:07:15.210
is an expert opinion or an anecdote.

149
00:07:16.260 --> 00:07:19.813
Now, keep in mind, sometimes the best evidence,

150
00:07:19.813 --> 00:07:22.473
all we have is a C.

151
00:07:23.610 --> 00:07:25.740
You know, a lot of times when I'm working with residents,

152
00:07:25.740 --> 00:07:26.756
you know, and we have journal club,

153
00:07:26.756 --> 00:07:29.250
they're like, oh, I can't do this paper

154
00:07:29.250 --> 00:07:31.860
because it's only a C recommendation.

155
00:07:31.860 --> 00:07:32.693
Okay.

156
00:07:32.693 --> 00:07:34.260
No, no, no, no, no, no, no, no.

157
00:07:34.260 --> 00:07:36.033
That's the best we have.

158
00:07:37.440 --> 00:07:38.853
We want an A.

159
00:07:39.930 --> 00:07:42.000
The best example of where, oh my gosh,

160
00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.120
I wish we'd have had the A before we employed the B

161
00:07:44.120 --> 00:07:45.930
is the Women's Health Initiative.

162
00:07:45.930 --> 00:07:47.583
So let's go back to that.

163
00:07:48.778 --> 00:07:53.778
Observational studies in the '70s and '80s,

164
00:07:54.360 --> 00:07:57.660
we're gonna say, demonstrated, oh my gosh,

165
00:07:57.660 --> 00:07:59.520
you know, women who are post-menopausal

166
00:07:59.520 --> 00:08:03.380
on hormone therapy have fewer cardiovascular events.

167
00:08:03.380 --> 00:08:06.600
That's what the observational data showed.

168
00:08:06.600 --> 00:08:09.400
So, you know, when I was in residency, like some of you,

169
00:08:10.997 --> 00:08:12.840
everybody who was post-menopausal

170
00:08:12.840 --> 00:08:14.010
got put on hormone therapy,

171
00:08:14.010 --> 00:08:16.013
didn't matter if you had symptoms or not.

172
00:08:16.890 --> 00:08:20.680
Then the randomized control trial is done.

173
00:08:20.680 --> 00:08:22.533
It's an eight-year study,

174
00:08:23.880 --> 00:08:25.380
hundreds of thousands of women

175
00:08:27.180 --> 00:08:30.300
and 5.8 years into the eight-year study,

176
00:08:30.300 --> 00:08:32.460
normal internal metrics,

177
00:08:32.460 --> 00:08:33.293
which are set up

178
00:08:33.293 --> 00:08:34.770
for any randomized controlled trial

179
00:08:34.770 --> 00:08:36.870
to make sure you're not hurting people

180
00:08:36.870 --> 00:08:41.520
were examined at a set point, as they always are.

181
00:08:41.520 --> 00:08:43.350
And people not involved in the study

182
00:08:43.350 --> 00:08:45.150
are looking at the data, right?

183
00:08:45.150 --> 00:08:46.890
You don't want anybody involved looking at it,

184
00:08:46.890 --> 00:08:50.279
you need to have individuals who are uninvolved,

185
00:08:50.279 --> 00:08:52.192
but they're experts in this field

186
00:08:52.192 --> 00:08:55.203
and they're like, oh my gosh,

187
00:08:56.430 --> 00:08:59.280
this was a primary prevention trial to say yes,

188
00:08:59.280 --> 00:09:00.630
women who were on hormone therapy

189
00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:02.280
had fewer cardiovascular events

190
00:09:02.280 --> 00:09:04.230
and it was just the opposite.

191
00:09:04.230 --> 00:09:08.318
The women in the hormone arm, in the active arm,

192
00:09:08.318 --> 00:09:12.390
were dying more often and having more heart attacks.

193
00:09:12.390 --> 00:09:14.590
So the study was stopped abruptly

194
00:09:16.920 --> 00:09:19.110
and published within four weeks.

195
00:09:19.110 --> 00:09:21.180
Okay, don't do this anymore.

196
00:09:21.180 --> 00:09:22.503
We're harming people.

197
00:09:23.640 --> 00:09:25.410
You know, another example of this is,

198
00:09:25.410 --> 00:09:28.020
if you go back to the '60s and the early '70s

199
00:09:28.020 --> 00:09:29.820
when electronic fetal monitoring

200
00:09:29.820 --> 00:09:31.170
continuously was introduced,

201
00:09:31.170 --> 00:09:32.400
you guys remember some of that?

202
00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:36.024
You know, mom is having dinner,

203
00:09:36.024 --> 00:09:38.790
she's 39 and a half weeks, she's having dinner,

204
00:09:38.790 --> 00:09:41.070
she's out, I don't know, where'd she go?

205
00:09:41.070 --> 00:09:43.983
Outback, she's having a steak.

206
00:09:44.850 --> 00:09:47.334
All of a sudden her membranes rupture

207
00:09:47.334 --> 00:09:48.720
and the next thing you know,

208
00:09:48.720 --> 00:09:53.720
she's in a gown tied down to a bed because she's sick.

209
00:09:54.960 --> 00:09:57.900
I.e. she's about to deliver a baby, okay?

210
00:09:57.900 --> 00:10:00.210
So you know, we use continuous electronic fetal monitoring

211
00:10:00.210 --> 00:10:02.460
because the observational data showed, oh my gosh,

212
00:10:02.460 --> 00:10:04.396
those women who have continuous electronic fetal monitoring,

213
00:10:04.396 --> 00:10:07.923
their kids are less likely to have CP or cerebral palsy.

214
00:10:09.335 --> 00:10:11.880
10 randomized controlled trials were done

215
00:10:11.880 --> 00:10:15.120
after that technology was introduced.

216
00:10:15.120 --> 00:10:18.153
Nine of the 10 showed no difference in outcomes.

217
00:10:19.170 --> 00:10:20.730
But what do we do today?

218
00:10:20.730 --> 00:10:22.320
We still do it.

219
00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:23.490
And it's gotten even worse now

220
00:10:23.490 --> 00:10:26.119
'cause they can monitor from the desk.

221
00:10:26.119 --> 00:10:27.000
Okay?

222
00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:29.070
So now you go into the room,

223
00:10:29.070 --> 00:10:30.150
the patient's tied down

224
00:10:30.150 --> 00:10:33.183
and there's not a soul in sight sometimes,

225
00:10:34.050 --> 00:10:38.550
dad's down getting coffee, support person is down,

226
00:10:38.550 --> 00:10:41.520
having a, I don't know, having a Pop-Tart or something.

227
00:10:41.520 --> 00:10:42.363
Who knows?

228
00:10:43.350 --> 00:10:46.413
Thank God for doulas, okay.

229
00:10:48.330 --> 00:10:51.142
So measures of risk,

230
00:10:51.142 --> 00:10:56.142
there are essentially two of them we have to worry about,

231
00:10:56.820 --> 00:10:59.943
relative risk and absolute risk.

232
00:11:01.110 --> 00:11:03.840
Now, anytime that you talk to anybody

233
00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:06.540
in the field of pharmaceuticals,

234
00:11:06.540 --> 00:11:09.450
they're always going to present to you an absolute risk,

235
00:11:09.450 --> 00:11:11.163
or excuse me, a relative risk.

236
00:11:12.660 --> 00:11:15.090
You know, you're 39% more likely

237
00:11:15.090 --> 00:11:17.400
not to have something if you take this medication,

238
00:11:17.400 --> 00:11:18.557
for example.

239
00:11:18.557 --> 00:11:20.927
But when you look at the event rate,

240
00:11:20.927 --> 00:11:23.523
that is the absolute risk,

241
00:11:25.410 --> 00:11:26.580
it's quite tiny.

242
00:11:26.580 --> 00:11:29.273
You know, one per 1,000 or something.

243
00:11:29.273 --> 00:11:32.730
Now, when you look at absolute risk, so for example,

244
00:11:32.730 --> 00:11:34.920
I said when you look at the women

245
00:11:34.920 --> 00:11:36.090
in the Women's Health Initiative

246
00:11:36.090 --> 00:11:39.356
who were on both estrogen and progesterone,

247
00:11:39.356 --> 00:11:42.573
those were the group at increased risk for breast cancer.

248
00:11:43.410 --> 00:11:46.080
The absolute risk was nine per 10,000.

249
00:11:46.080 --> 00:11:48.060
Now you think, well that's a tiny number,

250
00:11:48.060 --> 00:11:51.330
but when you take the total population

251
00:11:51.330 --> 00:11:54.090
of postmenopausal women in the world

252
00:11:54.090 --> 00:11:56.850
divided by 10,000 times nine,

253
00:11:56.850 --> 00:12:00.933
that number becomes exponentially large very quickly.

254
00:12:02.700 --> 00:12:04.860
So what we are always interested though,

255
00:12:04.860 --> 00:12:07.590
is in the absolute risk.

256
00:12:07.590 --> 00:12:11.070
The problem is when you look at absolute risk,

257
00:12:11.070 --> 00:12:14.288
because typically it's a very tiny number,

258
00:12:14.288 --> 00:12:17.673
you look at an absolute risk and it's like .0159.

259
00:12:20.550 --> 00:12:22.800
Well, now you try to explain that to the patient.

260
00:12:22.800 --> 00:12:26.190
Yeah, the absolute risk is .0159.

261
00:12:26.190 --> 00:12:27.790
What in the heck does that mean?

262
00:12:28.650 --> 00:12:29.880
So statistically,

263
00:12:29.880 --> 00:12:32.153
we've developed a number

264
00:12:36.470 --> 00:12:40.377
that speaks to us more than .0159

265
00:12:40.377 --> 00:12:43.383
and that's what's called the number needed to treat.

266
00:12:44.610 --> 00:12:45.900
So that's what we're gonna look at

