00:17:04.320 --> 00:17:06.813
This is a retrospective study.

362
00:17:10.800 --> 00:17:12.780
Consider a study that examines the risk factors

363
00:17:12.780 --> 00:17:14.220
for breast cancer among women

364
00:17:14.220 --> 00:17:16.020
participating in the first National Health

365
00:17:16.020 --> 00:17:17.670
and Nutrition Examination Survey.

366
00:17:18.510 --> 00:17:21.180
In a sample of 4,540 women who gave birth

367
00:17:21.180 --> 00:17:23.520
to their first child before the age of 25,

368
00:17:23.520 --> 00:17:25.736
65 developed breast cancer.

369
00:17:25.736 --> 00:17:27.930
Of the 1,628 women

370
00:17:27.930 --> 00:17:30.762
who first gave birth at age 25 or older,

371
00:17:30.762 --> 00:17:33.300
31 were diagnosed with breast cancer.

372
00:17:33.300 --> 00:17:34.507
So already you're thinking,

373
00:17:34.507 --> 00:17:37.590
"Hmm, this study is considering,

374
00:17:37.590 --> 00:17:42.590
is there some relationship between age at first child birth

375
00:17:42.750 --> 00:17:45.630
and breast cancer?"

376
00:17:45.630 --> 00:17:47.700
Okay, that is a typo there.

377
00:17:47.700 --> 00:17:49.710
That should be a retrospective cohort study.

378
00:17:49.710 --> 00:17:50.880
You can make that change.

379
00:17:50.880 --> 00:17:52.080
I apologize about that.

380
00:17:52.080 --> 00:17:54.420
It should say retrospective cohort study.

381
00:17:54.420 --> 00:17:58.770
Overall, and the reason that's there,

382
00:17:58.770 --> 00:18:00.420
what we have is a retrospective.

383
00:18:00.420 --> 00:18:05.420
The National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey overall

384
00:18:05.910 --> 00:18:08.820
was a prospective cohort study

385
00:18:08.820 --> 00:18:10.890
'cause it's a study that's going on, okay?

386
00:18:10.890 --> 00:18:12.759
It's a prospective one,

387
00:18:12.759 --> 00:18:16.080
but in any database

388
00:18:16.080 --> 00:18:18.660
you can go back and take a look at other issues

389
00:18:18.660 --> 00:18:21.210
that you might be interested in potentially.

390
00:18:21.210 --> 00:18:25.830
And that's why the aspect of the study we're looking at now

391
00:18:25.830 --> 00:18:27.393
is a retrospective.

392
00:18:28.560 --> 00:18:30.690
They had already given birth, okay?

393
00:18:30.690 --> 00:18:32.250
And you knew what age they gave birth at.

394
00:18:32.250 --> 00:18:33.240
Does that make sense?

395
00:18:33.240 --> 00:18:35.760
So overall, the National Health

396
00:18:35.760 --> 00:18:38.793
and Nutrition Examination Survey is a prospective study,

397
00:18:39.660 --> 00:18:42.248
but this particular entity of this study

398
00:18:42.248 --> 00:18:45.153
is a retrospective component of it.

399
00:18:48.210 --> 00:18:49.043
Okay.

400
00:18:50.160 --> 00:18:54.123
So what's the exposure?

401
00:18:55.157 --> 00:18:59.328
The researchers define this.

402
00:18:59.328 --> 00:19:01.800
It is the condition of having

403
00:19:01.800 --> 00:19:05.070
or first given birth at age 25 or older.

404
00:19:05.070 --> 00:19:07.134
They could have defined it in the opposite way,

405
00:19:07.134 --> 00:19:10.890
but this is defined the way they wanted to define it.

406
00:19:10.890 --> 00:19:15.890
So that's our exposure, first birth at age 25 or older.

407
00:19:19.710 --> 00:19:22.290
So we've got an observational study,

408
00:19:22.290 --> 00:19:24.480
we know what the exposure is,

409
00:19:24.480 --> 00:19:25.590
we've got two groups of women

410
00:19:25.590 --> 00:19:27.210
and we know what the outcome is,

411
00:19:27.210 --> 00:19:30.060
we can now construct a two by two contingency table

412
00:19:30.060 --> 00:19:32.280
and estimate the relative risk.

413
00:19:32.280 --> 00:19:36.330
So I'm looking at those who were diseased,

414
00:19:36.330 --> 00:19:40.020
have breast cancer, exposed to the factor,

415
00:19:40.020 --> 00:19:41.730
unexposed to the factor.

416
00:19:41.730 --> 00:19:42.810
Did you develop the disease

417
00:19:42.810 --> 00:19:44.490
or did you not develop the disease?

418
00:19:44.490 --> 00:19:48.780
Okay, initially they were looking at the disease free women,

419
00:19:48.780 --> 00:19:50.940
but then this particular entity

420
00:19:50.940 --> 00:19:52.923
looked at those who had the disease.

421
00:19:54.030 --> 00:19:58.743
Okay, now here's how we calculate the relative risk.

422
00:20:00.930 --> 00:20:04.600
It is a ratio of the experimental event rate

423
00:20:05.864 --> 00:20:08.133
to the control event rate.

424
00:20:11.010 --> 00:20:12.710
What's the event we're looking at?

425
00:20:16.500 --> 00:20:18.990
What's the event we're looking at here?

426
00:20:18.990 --> 00:20:19.983
Breast cancer.

427
00:20:21.990 --> 00:20:23.373
and what's the exposure?

428
00:20:24.660 --> 00:20:26.043
Older or younger.

429
00:20:27.240 --> 00:20:28.683
Pretty straightforward.

430
00:20:30.240 --> 00:20:35.240
Okay, the relative risk is a ratio of the incidence.

431
00:20:37.692 --> 00:20:39.993
The incidence is the rate.

432
00:20:41.430 --> 00:20:42.690
Experimental event rate

433
00:20:42.690 --> 00:20:44.820
divided by the control event rate.

434
00:20:44.820 --> 00:20:47.373
So there's that initial two by two table.

435
00:20:49.140 --> 00:20:53.220
I know that the experimental event rate, by definition,

436
00:20:53.220 --> 00:20:56.970
given that initial table is A divided by A plus C,

437
00:20:56.970 --> 00:20:59.190
that's the incidence rate.

438
00:20:59.190 --> 00:21:03.240
The control event rate is B divided by B plus D.

439
00:21:03.240 --> 00:21:05.670
That's the control event rate.

440
00:21:05.670 --> 00:21:07.500
If I do the ratio of those,

441
00:21:07.500 --> 00:21:09.933
I can estimate the relative risk.

442
00:21:12.240 --> 00:21:15.183
Okay, they gave me all those numbers.

443
00:21:16.800 --> 00:21:20.343
They told me 31 and 65,

444
00:21:21.450 --> 00:21:23.250
they told me the totals,

445
00:21:23.250 --> 00:21:24.900
so if I've got A and B

446
00:21:24.900 --> 00:21:27.630
and I know the totals of exposure to the factor,

447
00:21:27.630 --> 00:21:31.813
I can get C and D by simple subtraction,

448
00:21:31.813 --> 00:21:36.780
1,628 minus 31, 4,540 minus 65,

449
00:21:36.780 --> 00:21:39.757
and I get the cells C and D.

450
00:21:39.757 --> 00:21:42.483
All the numbers were given to me.

451
00:21:44.280 --> 00:21:46.323
Now I just plug 'em into my equation.

452
00:21:48.966 --> 00:21:53.966
31 over 1,628 divided by 65 over 4,540.

453
00:21:55.470 --> 00:21:57.270
Using that equation

454
00:21:57.270 --> 00:22:00.813
and I come up with a relative risk of 1.33.

455
00:22:02.700 --> 00:22:04.173
What does that mean?

456
00:22:05.280 --> 00:22:07.920
Women who gave birth at 25 years of age or older

457
00:22:07.920 --> 00:22:11.220
are 33% more likely to develop breast cancer

458
00:22:11.220 --> 00:22:13.893
than women who gave birth at a younger age.

459
00:22:17.970 --> 00:22:20.040
So I have a simple two by two table,

460
00:22:20.040 --> 00:22:22.067
I know what the exposure is defined as

461
00:22:22.067 --> 00:22:24.930
'cause they have to tell me that.

462
00:22:24.930 --> 00:22:27.180
And they gave me the number of people who developed cancer

463
00:22:27.180 --> 00:22:30.000
and the total number of women in each group.

464
00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:32.310
So I'm able to quickly set up that table.

465
00:22:32.310 --> 00:22:36.273
Now that 1.33 is what we call point estimate.

466
00:22:38.641 --> 00:22:42.180
Now we're not going to calculate this,

467
00:22:42.180 --> 00:22:43.830
but around any point estimate,

468
00:22:43.830 --> 00:22:45.990
regardless of what you're calculating,

469
00:22:45.990 --> 00:22:48.933
you can calculate something called a confidence interval.

470
00:22:51.510 --> 00:22:54.300
You do not need to know how to calculate this,

471
00:22:54.300 --> 00:22:56.013
but you need to understand it.

472
00:23:01.830 --> 00:23:04.570
So let's say our point estimate is 1.33

473
00:23:06.081 --> 00:23:08.640
and they tell you that the confidence interval

474
00:23:08.640 --> 00:23:13.153
around that is 1.21 to 1.63, which encompasses 1.33.

475
00:23:14.880 --> 00:23:19.880
What that means is there's at least a 21% chance,

476
00:23:22.830 --> 00:23:26.460
or there is at least women who developed,

477
00:23:26.460 --> 00:23:28.620
who had their first child, 25 or older,

478
00:23:28.620 --> 00:23:32.610
are at least 21% more likely to develop breast cancer

479
00:23:32.610 --> 00:23:35.220
and as much as 63% more likely

480
00:23:35.220 --> 00:23:39.030
to develop breast cancer than those who had a child younger.

481
00:23:39.030 --> 00:23:42.850
Our best estimate of what the actual risk is is 33%

482
00:23:46.230 --> 00:23:50.910
'cause there's a statistical range

483
00:23:50.910 --> 00:23:52.893
around any point estimate.

484
00:23:54.180 --> 00:23:57.900
Now, let's say they told you the confidence interval

485
00:23:57.900 --> 00:24:01.983
was 0.89 to 1.63.

486
00:24:04.170 --> 00:24:06.210
Anytime a confidence interval

487
00:24:06.210 --> 00:24:08.883
around a point estimate crosses one,

488
00:24:10.560 --> 00:24:13.032
there's a probability that that breast cancer

489
00:24:13.032 --> 00:24:16.023
is unrelated to the exposure.

490
00:24:18.330 --> 00:24:19.500
Because what you're saying

491
00:24:19.500 --> 00:24:22.110
is the probabilities of the disease

492
00:24:22.110 --> 00:24:23.910
and the exposed group and the unexposed group,

493
00:24:23.910 --> 00:24:27.123
if it's one, is exactly the same.

494
00:24:30.390 --> 00:24:32.373
Your brow is furrowed.

495
00:24:33.420 --> 00:24:34.743
Not making sense, is it?

496
00:24:37.410 --> 00:24:41.340
Okay, so whenever a confidence interval crosses one,

497
00:24:41.340 --> 00:24:45.180
you're essentially saying there is a possibility

498
00:24:45.180 --> 00:24:48.573
there's no difference between the groups.

499
00:24:50.700 --> 00:24:53.100
Now why is there no difference?

500
00:24:53.100 --> 00:24:55.350
Maybe I don't have a large enough sample size

501
00:24:56.340 --> 00:24:58.233
or maybe there's no difference.

502
00:24:59.580 --> 00:25:01.620
Well, if I know I have a large enough sample size,

503
00:25:01.620 --> 00:25:03.510
I know there's no difference,

504
00:25:03.510 --> 00:25:05.280
that factor does not make any difference

505
00:25:05.280 --> 00:25:07.113
in this outcome I'm looking at.

506
00:25:08.280 --> 00:25:09.113
Okay?

507
00:25:10.740 --> 00:25:13.350
So regardless of what you're reading,

508
00:25:13.350 --> 00:25:15.633
if the confidence interval crosses one,

509
00:25:16.745 --> 00:25:20.583
there's the potential that the point estimate is one,

510
00:25:20.583 --> 00:25:23.343
and therefore there's no difference between the groups.

511
00:25:25.350 --> 00:25:26.850
Let's try this question.

512
00:25:26.850 --> 00:25:28.230
The results of a given study report

513
00:25:28.230 --> 00:25:31.310
is achieving a significance at a P-value of less than .05,

514
00:25:31.310 --> 00:25:32.580
the 5% level.

515
00:25:32.580 --> 00:25:33.960
True statements about this finding

516
00:25:33.960 --> 00:25:35.880
include which one of the following?

517
00:25:35.880 --> 00:25:38.100
I had to throw this in there someplace.

518
00:25:38.100 --> 00:25:39.660
There's a 5% likelihood of the results

519
00:25:39.660 --> 00:25:41.040
having occurred by chance alone.

520
00:25:41.040 --> 00:25:42.810
If the study were replicated 100 times,

521
00:25:42.810 --> 00:25:46.230
95 studies would repeat this finding and five would not.

522
00:25:46.230 --> 00:25:48.390
The confidence interval is zero to 10%

523
00:25:48.390 --> 00:25:51.603
or the null hypothesis has a 5% chance of being true.

524
00:25:57.480 --> 00:25:59.763
So that's what a P-value means.

525
00:26:01.410 --> 00:26:05.040
Now, and a researcher, an experimenter,

526
00:26:05.040 --> 00:26:07.390
they can set the P-value wherever they want it.

527
00:26:09.030 --> 00:26:12.363
But remember, here's the hypothesis going into a study,

528
00:26:13.530 --> 00:26:15.573
it's always the null hypothesis.

529
00:26:17.730 --> 00:26:19.780
There's no difference between the groups.

530
00:26:20.940 --> 00:26:23.729
Regardless of what I'm trying to demonstrate,

531
00:26:23.729 --> 00:26:25.113
there's no difference.

532
00:26:26.550 --> 00:26:28.200
'Cause what am I trying to prove?

533
00:26:29.130 --> 00:26:32.310
There is a difference based on medicine they're taking

534
00:26:32.310 --> 00:26:33.843
or a study they're taking.

535
00:26:36.030 --> 00:26:38.460
I want everybody just to relax your brows right now.

536
00:26:38.460 --> 00:26:39.930
You are not gonna make it through this day,

537
00:26:39.930 --> 00:26:43.260
your brow, just relax them, it's fine.

538
00:26:43.260 --> 00:26:47.853
Just go to someplace that's not here right now, okay?

539
00:26:49.140 --> 00:26:52.113
The P-value can be set at any level.

540
00:26:53.940 --> 00:26:58.940
I can set that at 5%, 1%, 1/10 of 1%, 10%.

541
00:27:03.750 --> 00:27:07.473
It is a level of statistical significance.

542
00:27:09.570 --> 00:27:11.223
And what it says is,

543
00:27:12.150 --> 00:27:13.800
I'm thinking that the difference

544
00:27:13.800 --> 00:27:14.880
in between these two groups

545
00:27:14.880 --> 00:27:18.153
was secondary to some factor or drug.

546
00:27:19.650 --> 00:27:22.830
I'm willing to accept a 5% or 1%

547
00:27:22.830 --> 00:27:27.390
or 10% chance that by chance alone

548
00:27:27.390 --> 00:27:28.953
I'm seeing this difference,

549
00:27:30.360 --> 00:27:33.240
has nothing to do with what I thought.

550
00:27:33.240 --> 00:27:38.193
It's just random chance, okay?

551
00:27:39.900 --> 00:27:42.240
Sometimes you'll see the P-value.

552
00:27:42.240 --> 00:27:45.300
Now I set my P-value at 5%.

553
00:27:45.300 --> 00:27:47.019
I'm willing to take a risk of 5%

554
00:27:47.019 --> 00:27:51.270
and when I calculate my P-value around my estimate,

555
00:27:51.270 --> 00:27:54.363
the P-value comes out to 0.00001.

556
00:27:55.530 --> 00:27:58.620
Then I know the risk of this being secondary

557
00:27:58.620 --> 00:28:02.013
to chance alone is one in a million.

558
00:28:03.271 --> 00:28:07.350
I'm not a betting person, but if I were a betting person,

559
00:28:07.350 --> 00:28:09.000
I wouldn't be down on the strip in Vegas,

560
00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:12.258
betting a lot if my chances of winning was one in a million.

561
00:28:12.258 --> 00:28:15.330
That's why I'm better at retail therapy.

562
00:28:15.330 --> 00:28:16.830
I go across the street to the place

563
00:28:16.830 --> 00:28:20.130
where you get that turquoise bag,

564
00:28:20.130 --> 00:28:22.230
much better to leave there with that.

565
00:28:22.230 --> 00:28:23.063
Some people are thinking,

566
00:28:23.063 --> 00:28:24.490
what the heck's a turquoise bag?

567
00:28:26.370 --> 00:28:29.100
Okay, so the confidence interval,

568
00:28:29.100 --> 00:28:31.323
you can have around a P-value also,

569
00:28:32.250 --> 00:28:34.140
but the P-value itself says nothing

570
00:28:34.140 --> 00:28:38.130
about the truth or falsity of the null hypothesis.

571
00:28:38.130 --> 00:28:41.670
The null hypothesis is still, there's no difference.

572
00:28:41.670 --> 00:28:45.561
It's just if there is a difference,

573
00:28:45.561 --> 00:28:47.883
how much risk am I willing to accept

574
00:28:47.883 --> 00:28:50.733
that that difference is secondary to chance alone?

575
00:28:51.990 --> 00:28:52.823
Okay?

576
00:28:55.254 --> 00:28:57.210
Now, why do we need to know the difference

577
00:28:57.210 --> 00:28:58.230
between this relative risk,

578
00:28:58.230 --> 00:28:59.490
absolute risk, and number needed to treat?

579
00:28:59.490 --> 00:29:04.080
As I said, it is because the relative risk tends

580
00:29:04.080 --> 00:29:06.240
to amplify very small differences.

581
00:29:06.240 --> 00:29:08.082
These can be clinically insignificant

582
00:29:08.082 --> 00:29:12.923
and it sounds really significant.

583
00:29:12.923 --> 00:29:15.513
They're 50% more likely not to.

584
00:29:16.735 --> 00:29:18.960
The absolute risk reduction

585
00:29:18.960 --> 00:29:20.010
and the number needed to treat,

586
00:29:20.010 --> 00:29:21.810
that is what gives you a much better appreciation

587
00:29:21.810 --> 00:29:23.820
of the magnitude of this.

588
00:29:23.820 --> 00:29:26.520
It could be a benefit, it could be a potential impact.

589
00:29:27.450 --> 00:29:30.690
And like I said, you should be able to,

590
00:29:30.690 --> 00:29:33.540
if they have calculated

591
00:29:33.540 --> 00:29:35.970
an absolute risk reduction in the paper

592
00:29:35.970 --> 00:29:37.980
and a number needed to treat in the paper

593
00:29:37.980 --> 00:29:39.030
that's being published,

594
00:29:39.030 --> 00:29:41.490
you should be able to calculate it yourself.

595
00:29:41.490 --> 00:29:42.990
There should be no confusion.

596
00:29:42.990 --> 00:29:44.940
Good morning, Dr. Hold.

597
00:29:44.940 --> 00:29:47.124
She's back, she's like, "Oh, this is really good."

598
00:29:47.124 --> 00:29:49.290
(chuckles)

599
00:29:49.290 --> 00:29:50.123
Okay.

600
00:29:51.690 --> 00:29:56.690
Now, the absolute risk reduction is simply not in ratio,

601
00:29:57.600 --> 00:29:59.973
it's simple subtraction.

602
00:30:00.870 --> 00:30:02.670
I'm gonna subtract my control event

603
00:30:02.670 --> 00:30:05.820
or my experimental event rate from the control event rate.

604
00:30:05.820 --> 00:30:09.360
So instead of comparing the rates via division,

605
00:30:09.360 --> 00:30:11.313
I'm gonna compare them by subtraction.

606
00:30:12.359 --> 00:30:14.580
Now as I said, when you look at those numbers,

607
00:30:14.580 --> 00:30:16.134
you're like, "Well, that doesn't make any sense."

608
00:30:16.134 --> 00:30:17.940
The number needed to treat

609
00:30:17.940 --> 00:30:21.033
is simply an inverse of the absolute risk reduction.

610
00:30:25.380 --> 00:30:26.213
Okay?

611
00:30:26.213 --> 00:30:27.900
So those are the three formulas, okay.

612
00:30:27.900 --> 00:30:29.430
So let's take a look at that.

613
00:30:29.430 --> 00:30:31.080
You are considering how beneficial

614
00:30:31.080 --> 00:30:32.910
a new treatment might be in preventing stroke.

615
00:30:32.910 --> 00:30:35.070
A well-designed study was reported

616
00:30:35.070 --> 00:30:36.420
with 200 patients in the treated group

617
00:30:36.420 --> 00:30:38.070
and 200 patients in the untreated group.

618
00:30:38.070 --> 00:30:40.620
The study finds a five-year risk of stroke of 3%

619
00:30:40.620 --> 00:30:43.413
in the treated group versus 5% in the untreated group.

620
00:30:44.310 --> 00:30:46.050
Assuming this study is valid and applicable

621
00:30:46.050 --> 00:30:47.130
to your patient population,

622
00:30:47.130 --> 00:30:48.607
how many patients would you have to treat

623
00:30:48.607 --> 00:30:51.273
for five years to prevent one stroke?

624
00:30:56.670 --> 00:30:58.170
There you go.

625
00:30:58.170 --> 00:31:02.250
Correct answer is 50, 50.

626
00:31:02.250 --> 00:31:03.783
So how did we do that?

627
00:31:05.340 --> 00:31:07.410
The control event rate was 5%,

628
00:31:07.410 --> 00:31:09.720
the experimental event rate was 3%,

629
00:31:09.720 --> 00:31:11.193
five minus three,

630
00:31:13.050 --> 00:31:14.010
2%.

631
00:31:14.010 --> 00:31:15.450
Now we had to go to percentages.

632
00:31:15.450 --> 00:31:16.500
So instead of one over,

633
00:31:16.500 --> 00:31:19.563
we do 100 over and that equals 50.

634
00:31:22.410 --> 00:31:23.243
You're thinking now,

635
00:31:23.243 --> 00:31:25.020
"Oh well, I should have been able to do that."

636
00:31:25.020 --> 00:31:26.520
He gave me the control event rate,

637
00:31:26.520 --> 00:31:28.920
the experimental event rate, and I do the inverse of that.

638
00:31:28.920 --> 00:31:30.960
That's all you have to do.

639
00:31:30.960 --> 00:31:33.240
Now, you could have done that without a calculator.

640
00:31:33.240 --> 00:31:36.308
So this could be a question you could do on the exam.

641
00:31:36.308 --> 00:31:40.353
They're not gonna give you weird numbers, okay.

642
00:31:41.220 --> 00:31:42.960
The absolute risk reduction is the difference

643
00:31:42.960 --> 00:31:45.240
between the incidence of disease in the treatment group

644
00:31:45.240 --> 00:31:47.463
and the incidence in the control group.

645
00:31:52.466 --> 00:31:54.000
Absolute risk reduction

646
00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:55.380
or the number needed to treat

647
00:31:55.380 --> 00:31:57.153
is simply the reciprocal of that.

648
00:31:58.200 --> 00:32:00.213
That's all it is.

649
00:32:01.680 --> 00:32:04.320
Results of a clinical study show a relative risk reduction

650
00:32:04.320 --> 00:32:09.320
of 33% and an absolute risk reduction of 0.2 or 20%.

651
00:32:09.479 --> 00:32:11.520
There are 1,000 patients each in the treatment

652
00:32:11.520 --> 00:32:12.353
and control groups.

653
00:32:12.353 --> 00:32:14.671
To help determine the potential benefit of the treatment,

654
00:32:14.671 --> 00:32:17.490
it is necessary to identify the number needed to treat.

655
00:32:17.490 --> 00:32:18.360
Which one of the following

656
00:32:18.360 --> 00:32:19.680
is the number needed to treat for this study?

657
00:32:19.680 --> 00:32:21.723
3, 5, 13, or you can't determine it?

658
00:32:23.490 --> 00:32:25.701
Remember, this is the way it will always be.

659
00:32:25.701 --> 00:32:30.701
Answer D or E is never all the above or none of the above.

660
00:32:30.774 --> 00:32:31.893
Okay?

661
00:32:35.760 --> 00:32:36.780
Okay, good.

662
00:32:36.780 --> 00:32:37.860
Five.

663
00:32:37.860 --> 00:32:39.153
So let's take a look.

664
00:32:41.130 --> 00:32:44.940
100% divided by 20% equals five

665
00:32:44.940 --> 00:32:48.450
'cause they gave you what the absolute risk reduction was.

666
00:32:48.450 --> 00:32:50.343
So I just gotta do the inverse of it.

667
00:32:57.480 --> 00:33:02.100
Okay, let's try this with the Women's Health Initiative

668
00:33:02.100 --> 00:33:04.773
and we're gonna calculate the number needed to harm.

669
00:33:07.980 --> 00:33:10.590
Now this is a primary prevention trial,

670
00:33:10.590 --> 00:33:12.960
was looking at the role of estrogen and progesterone

671
00:33:12.960 --> 00:33:16.140
or estrogen alone in preventing cardiac events

672
00:33:16.140 --> 00:33:17.703
in postmenopausal women.

673
00:33:19.260 --> 00:33:21.300
Now I talk about this study so much

674
00:33:21.300 --> 00:33:24.990
because for those of you who don't know,

675
00:33:24.990 --> 00:33:28.950
this was a landmark study, okay?

676
00:33:28.950 --> 00:33:32.850
I mean, and for those of you who are of my era,

677
00:33:32.850 --> 00:33:35.490
finishing med school in the late '80s, early '90s,

678
00:33:35.490 --> 00:33:37.020
I mean, it's probably one of the biggest changes

679
00:33:37.020 --> 00:33:38.553
we've seen in our career.

680
00:33:42.210 --> 00:33:44.310
And when this study was published,

681
00:33:44.310 --> 00:33:47.550
we were literally on the phone calling people,

682
00:33:47.550 --> 00:33:49.953
telling them, please stop your hormone therapy.

683
00:33:50.795 --> 00:33:54.210
Now I spend a lot of time now talking about this

684
00:33:54.210 --> 00:33:56.730
because we're 21 years since this study

685
00:33:56.730 --> 00:33:58.770
and we've learned a lot in those women

686
00:33:58.770 --> 00:34:00.693
who have continued to be followed.

687
00:34:01.530 --> 00:34:03.870
So I have residents who come in who I'm like,

688
00:34:03.870 --> 00:34:06.937
okay, they've got vasomotor symptoms, they're miserable.

689
00:34:06.937 --> 00:34:08.880
"Oh, I don't use hormones, Dr. Weismiller."

690
00:34:08.880 --> 00:34:12.067
I'm like, "What? Why not?"

691
00:34:12.067 --> 00:34:13.830
"Well, the Women's Health Initiative."

692
00:34:13.830 --> 00:34:15.480
God.

693
00:34:15.480 --> 00:34:17.790
Or my favorite was, I mentioned this

694
00:34:17.790 --> 00:34:19.200
to a third-year medical student the other day

695
00:34:19.200 --> 00:34:21.837
and she's like, "What's the Women's Health Initiative?"

696
00:34:21.837 --> 00:34:23.880
(laughs)

697
00:34:23.880 --> 00:34:27.073
Okay, so the total number of women

698
00:34:27.073 --> 00:34:32.073
who were in the experimental arm

699
00:34:33.060 --> 00:34:35.793
receiving hormones was 8,506,

700
00:34:37.584 --> 00:34:40.290
had 164 events.

701
00:34:40.290 --> 00:34:44.073
Total of women receiving placebo, 8,102,

702
00:34:44.940 --> 00:34:46.803
122 cardiac events.

703
00:34:47.700 --> 00:34:50.220
Now, before somebody calls me out on something,

704
00:34:50.220 --> 00:34:52.143
just I wanna remind everybody though,

705
00:34:54.930 --> 00:34:58.173
this was not a perfect study by any means,

706
00:34:59.070 --> 00:35:01.740
and it will never be done again.

707
00:35:01.740 --> 00:35:03.922
Okay, it would be unethical.

708
00:35:03.922 --> 00:35:06.510
And part of the issue with this study,

709
00:35:06.510 --> 00:35:09.390
which is what we've learned over the last 18 years

710
00:35:09.390 --> 00:35:11.560
is that the women in the study were older

711
00:35:12.630 --> 00:35:14.460
and we now know starting hormone therapy

712
00:35:14.460 --> 00:35:18.600
closer to menopause, I.e. within 10 years

713
00:35:18.600 --> 00:35:22.560
or before the age of 60 is the safest.

714
00:35:22.560 --> 00:35:24.890
The risk outweighs the benefit when you're older than 60

715
00:35:24.890 --> 00:35:27.125
or more than 10 years from the last period.

716
00:35:27.125 --> 00:35:29.045
Okay?

717
00:35:29.045 --> 00:35:34.045
So we can calculate our relative risk

718
00:35:34.187 --> 00:35:37.110
'cause we can calculate the control event rate

719
00:35:37.110 --> 00:35:38.710
and the experimental event rate.

720
00:35:40.890 --> 00:35:43.833
Here, in calculating a number needed to harm,

721
00:35:45.570 --> 00:35:48.663
it's still the inverse of the absolute risk reduction,

722
00:35:49.920 --> 00:35:52.860
but we have to reverse it.

723
00:35:52.860 --> 00:35:54.600
And it is the experimental event rate

724
00:35:54.600 --> 00:35:55.980
minus the control event rate

725
00:35:55.980 --> 00:35:59.820
when we're looking at calculating number needed to harm.

726
00:35:59.820 --> 00:36:02.940
So it's the inverse, not of the control event rate

727
00:36:02.940 --> 00:36:04.620
minus the experimental event rate,

728
00:36:04.620 --> 00:36:06.270
that's the number needed to treat,

729
00:36:06.270 --> 00:36:09.150
but rather the inverse of the experimental event rate

730
00:36:09.150 --> 00:36:10.773
minus the control event rate.

731
00:36:14.490 --> 00:36:18.033
Okay, so here's our two by two table, again,

732
00:36:19.620 --> 00:36:21.870
our disease of interest on the y-axis,

733
00:36:21.870 --> 00:36:24.684
our exposure to the factor on the x-axis.

734
00:36:24.684 --> 00:36:25.950
(attendee sneezes)

735
00:36:25.950 --> 00:36:26.783
Bless you.

736
00:36:26.783 --> 00:36:29.823
Our exposure was estrogen or estrogen plus progesterone,

737
00:36:31.440 --> 00:36:33.213
or placebo.

738
00:36:34.290 --> 00:36:35.730
And I either had a cardiac event

739
00:36:35.730 --> 00:36:37.280
or didn't have a cardiac event.

740
00:36:40.350 --> 00:36:41.250
Pretty basic here.

741
00:36:41.250 --> 00:36:43.863
I mean this is not rocket science.

742
00:36:45.330 --> 00:36:49.983
Now when I do my calculation,

743
00:36:51.600 --> 00:36:56.430
it's 164 divided by 164 plus 8,342

744
00:36:56.430 --> 00:36:57.960
'cause that's gonna gimme my total

745
00:36:57.960 --> 00:36:59.940
of those who had an event

746
00:36:59.940 --> 00:37:03.510
divided by 122 over 122 plus 7,980.

747
00:37:03.510 --> 00:37:05.973
So that's my relative risk.

748
00:37:08.610 --> 00:37:13.610
Now, when I look at my experimental event rate

749
00:37:14.504 --> 00:37:17.160
divided by my control event rate,

750
00:37:17.160 --> 00:37:18.917
which is the relative risk, I get 1.26.

751
00:37:18.917 --> 00:37:22.230
So you were 26% more likely to have a heart attack

752
00:37:22.230 --> 00:37:24.933
or cardiovascular event if you are on hormone therapy.

753
00:37:26.119 --> 00:37:28.413
Now that's a point estimate.

754
00:37:30.300 --> 00:37:33.150
When I look at the absolute risk reduction or increase,

755
00:37:33.150 --> 00:37:34.890
which is what we saw here.

756
00:37:34.890 --> 00:37:37.800
We saw a .004 increase,

757
00:37:37.800 --> 00:37:40.170
well, that doesn't mean much to anybody.

758
00:37:40.170 --> 00:37:43.320
So we have to then calculate the number needed to harm,

759
00:37:43.320 --> 00:37:44.940
which is the experimental event rate

760
00:37:44.940 --> 00:37:47.153
minus the control event rate.

761
00:37:47.153 --> 00:37:52.153
The number needed to harm is one over that or 250.

762
00:37:54.180 --> 00:37:59.040
So I have to treat 250 people for 5.8 years with hormones

763
00:37:59.040 --> 00:38:01.323
to have one additional cardiovascular event.

764
00:38:03.090 --> 00:38:05.490
The number of post-menopausal people in the world

765
00:38:05.490 --> 00:38:09.900
divided by 250, problematic.

766
00:38:09.900 --> 00:38:12.450
That's why we stopped, okay?

767
00:38:12.450 --> 00:38:14.880
So that's the number needed to harm.

768
00:38:14.880 --> 00:38:17.760
We can't calculate the number needed to treat

769
00:38:17.760 --> 00:38:19.290
because we weren't treating anybody,

770
00:38:19.290 --> 00:38:20.670
we were harming them.

771
00:38:20.670 --> 00:38:21.503
Okay?

772
00:38:25.440 --> 00:38:30.440
Patients taking HRT for 5.2 years have a 26% more MIs.

773
00:38:31.627 --> 00:38:34.530
1.9% of patients taking HRT for 5.2 years

774
00:38:34.530 --> 00:38:37.980
had an MI compared to 1.5% not taking HT.

775
00:38:37.980 --> 00:38:41.370
If 250 women took HT for 5.2 years,

776
00:38:41.370 --> 00:38:43.620
the drug would cause one additional heart attack.

777
00:38:43.620 --> 00:38:46.923
They're the three parameters, okay?

778
00:38:48.030 --> 00:38:49.440
You can see why that number needed to harm

779
00:38:49.440 --> 00:38:52.320
and number needed to treat is so important.

780
00:38:52.320 --> 00:38:55.050
Now, there's no absolute number

781
00:38:55.050 --> 00:38:55.883
where the number needed to treat

782
00:38:55.883 --> 00:38:59.643
and number needed to harm is correct.

783
00:39:01.260 --> 00:39:05.130
Sometimes the number needed to treat of 1,000 is great.

784
00:39:05.130 --> 00:39:09.483
Sometimes the number needed to treat of 10 is great, okay?

785
00:39:10.920 --> 00:39:11.753
Okay.

786
00:39:12.720 --> 00:39:14.790
Cochrane Library periodically reviews the evidence

787
00:39:14.790 --> 00:39:17.760
of the effectiveness of mammography screening

788
00:39:17.760 --> 00:39:18.960
for the detection of breast cancer.

789
00:39:18.960 --> 00:39:20.970
One analysis from their 2006 review

790
00:39:20.970 --> 00:39:22.650
looked at deaths ascribed to breast cancer

791
00:39:22.650 --> 00:39:24.420
for women at least 50 years of age,

792
00:39:24.420 --> 00:39:25.860
who had screening mammography generally

793
00:39:25.860 --> 00:39:28.650
every one to three years compared with women who did not.

794
00:39:28.650 --> 00:39:30.270
After 13 years of follow up,

795
00:39:30.270 --> 00:39:34.860
595 out of 146,284 women in the screen group

796
00:39:34.860 --> 00:39:39.285
died of breast cancer compared with 701 of 122,590

797
00:39:39.285 --> 00:39:40.563
in the unscreened group.

798
00:39:41.940 --> 00:39:44.190
You're thinking, now how am I gonna do this math?

